    <!-- 8. Questions to Ask -->
    <section id="questions-to-ask" class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-cream">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Section 8</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-6">Questions to Ask</h2>

        <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-base mb-3">About the Executive and Working Style</h3>
        <div class="space-y-3 mb-6">
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-medium text-primary text-sm mb-1">"How does [executive name] prefer to receive information: quick Slack messages, scheduled briefings, or email summaries?"</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs italic">Reveals their communication style. If they say "email summaries," you know they want you to filter and synthesize. If "quick Slack," they want real-time updates.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-medium text-primary text-sm mb-1">"What did the previous EA do particularly well, and what do you wish they had done differently?"</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs italic">This is gold. It tells you exactly what the executive values and where the last person fell short. If they hesitate, that is a red flag about the working relationship.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-medium text-primary text-sm mb-1">"How does [executive name] handle urgent changes to the schedule? Do they prefer to be consulted on every reschedule, or do they trust their EA to make judgment calls?"</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs italic">Reveals how much autonomy you will have. EAs who can make decisions independently are valued more, and this question shows you expect to operate at that level.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-medium text-primary text-sm mb-1">"What does a typical week look like for the executive, and where does the EA add the most value?"</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs italic">Helps you understand whether this is a logistics-heavy role or a strategic-partnership role. If the answer is mostly calendar and travel, it may be below your level.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-base mb-3">About the Role and Team</h3>
        <div class="space-y-3 mb-6">
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-medium text-primary text-sm mb-1">"Is this a newly created position, or am I replacing someone? If replacing, why did they leave?"</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs italic">New position means undefined scope, which means either opportunity or chaos. Replacement means there is a mold to step into. If they fired the last person, you want to know why.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-medium text-primary text-sm mb-1">"What does success look like in the first 90 days for this role?"</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs italic">Shows you think about onboarding strategically and want to deliver results quickly. Also gives you a concrete benchmark to measure against.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-medium text-primary text-sm mb-1">"How does the EA function interact with other departments? Am I primarily supporting one person, or will I work across the leadership team?"</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs italic">Determines your scope and complexity. Supporting multiple leaders is harder but often more fulfilling and better compensated.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-medium text-primary text-sm mb-1">"Is there a path for this role to expand in scope, such as taking on project management or operational responsibilities?"</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs italic">Shows ambition without saying "I want to be promoted out of this role." Signals you want to grow within the partnership, not away from it.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-base mb-3">About Company Culture and Support</h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-medium text-primary text-sm mb-1">"How does the company invest in professional development for EAs? Are there conferences, training budgets, or mentorship programs?"</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs italic">Reveals how the company values EAs. If they have no answer, EAs may be seen as interchangeable rather than strategic.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-medium text-primary text-sm mb-1">"What tools and technology does the team use for communication, project management, and scheduling?"</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs italic">Practical question that shows you care about efficiency. Also lets you assess if their tech stack matches your skills.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-medium text-primary text-sm mb-1">"How would you describe the pace and culture of this team?"</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs italic">Filters for fit. "Fast-paced and high-pressure" means long hours. "Collaborative and structured" means more predictable. Neither is wrong, but you need to know what you are signing up for.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-medium text-primary text-sm mb-1">"What is one thing you wish candidates knew about this role before they accepted it?"</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs italic">The honesty question. Good interviewers will give you a real answer. If they dodge it, take note.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 9. Your Processes -->
    <section id="your-processes" class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-warm">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Section 9</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-6">Your Processes</h2>

        <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg mb-3">How I Onboard with a New Executive</h3>
        <p class="text-text-muted text-xs italic mb-3">Relevant to: first 90 days in a new EA role</p>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm mb-6">
          <ol class="space-y-3 text-sm text-text-muted list-decimal list-inside">
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Discovery Week:</span> In the first week, I schedule a dedicated 60-minute meeting with the executive to understand their communication preferences, calendar priorities, pet peeves, and how they define success. I also meet with their direct reports and key stakeholders.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">System Audit:</span> I review their existing calendar, filing system, and communication patterns. I identify what is working and what needs improvement, but I do not change anything yet.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Quick Wins (Weeks 2-4):</span> I implement 2-3 small improvements that demonstrate value without disrupting the flow. This could be a cleaner meeting structure, a standardized briefing format, or better travel templates.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Rhythm Building (Months 2-3):</span> I establish recurring touchpoints (daily morning brief, weekly priorities review, monthly calendar planning) and refine them based on the executive's feedback until we find our working rhythm.</li>
          </ol>
        </div>

        <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg mb-3">How I Prepare for Board Meetings</h3>
        <p class="text-text-muted text-xs italic mb-3">Relevant to: board coordination, investor relations</p>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm mb-6">
          <ol class="space-y-3 text-sm text-text-muted list-decimal list-inside">
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">T-minus 3 weeks:</span> Send materials request to all presenters with a template and firm deadline. Set up a shared folder with version control.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">T-minus 2 weeks:</span> First draft review. I check every slide for consistency, formatting, and completeness. Flag gaps to presenters.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">T-minus 1 week:</span> Final package assembly. Print and digital versions. Pre-read distributed to board members. Logistics confirmed (room, tech, catering, remote dial-in).</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Day of:</span> Arrive early to test AV, set up materials, and brief the executive on last-minute changes. During the meeting, take detailed notes on action items. Post-meeting, distribute minutes and action tracker within 24 hours.</li>
          </ol>
        </div>

        <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg mb-3">How I Manage Competing Priorities</h3>
        <p class="text-text-muted text-xs italic mb-3">Relevant to: calendar management, multiple stakeholders</p>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm mb-6">
          <ol class="space-y-3 text-sm text-text-muted list-decimal list-inside">
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Triage:</span> Every incoming request gets categorized as urgent/important, important/not urgent, urgent/not important, or neither. I handle the first category immediately and schedule the rest.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Visible Prioritization:</span> I maintain a shared priority board (Asana or Monday.com) so the executive and I are always aligned on what matters this week. No surprises.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Proactive Communication:</span> When conflicts arise, I do not wait for the executive to notice. I present the conflict with a recommended resolution: "You have two overlapping meetings Thursday. I recommend moving the vendor call to Friday because the board prep is time-sensitive. Want me to handle that?"</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">End-of-Day Check:</span> A 2-minute end-of-day message to the executive summarizing what was completed, what shifted, and what is on deck for tomorrow.</li>
          </ol>
        </div>

        <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg mb-3">How I Handle Confidential Information</h3>
        <p class="text-text-muted text-xs italic mb-3">Relevant to: discretion, trust, investor relations</p>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
          <ol class="space-y-3 text-sm text-text-muted list-decimal list-inside">
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Default to Confidential:</span> I treat all executive communications as confidential unless explicitly told otherwise. This is especially critical in investor relations, M&A, and HR matters.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Access Controls:</span> Sensitive documents go in restricted folders. I control permissions and audit access regularly. No shared drives for confidential materials.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Need-to-Know Communication:</span> When relaying information to other team members, I share only what they need to complete their task, not the full context. I am deliberate about what details I include in emails, Slack messages, and meeting notes.</li>
          </ol>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 10. Interview Strategy -->
    <section id="interview-strategy" class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-cream">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Section 10</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-6">Interview Strategy</h2>

        <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg mb-3">What You Need to Learn About Them</h3>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm mb-6">
          <p class="text-text-muted text-sm mb-3">Before accepting any EA role, you should have clear answers to these questions:</p>
          <ol class="space-y-3 text-sm text-text-muted list-decimal list-inside">
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">How does the executive actually work?</span> Not the job description version. The real version. Are they a 6am emailer? A last-minute changer? A micromanager? Ask the recruiter, ask in the interview, and read between the lines.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Why did the last EA leave?</span> If they were fired, was it a skills issue or a personality mismatch? If they left voluntarily, what drove them away? This is the single most important piece of intelligence you can gather.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">How are EAs valued in this organization?</span> Are they included in team meetings? Do they have a development budget? Is the role seen as a career or a stepping stone? The answer tells you everything about your ceiling here.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">What is the real remote/hybrid expectation?</span> "Hybrid" means different things at different companies. Get the specific days and the flexibility around them.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">What is the team dynamic?</span> Will you work closely with other EAs? Is there a head of admin or EA manager? Or are you on an island? Isolation can be draining in EA roles.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">What is the growth trajectory?</span> Not just for you, but for the company. A growing company means expanding scope. A flat or shrinking company means you might be doing more with less.</li>
          </ol>
        </div>

        <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg mb-3">What They Need to Know About You</h3>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm mb-6">
          <p class="text-text-muted text-sm mb-3">In every interview, make sure these messages come through:</p>
          <ol class="space-y-3 text-sm text-text-muted list-decimal list-inside">
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">You have board-level experience.</span> Not every EA does. Make sure they know you have prepared board materials, managed investor communications, and operated at the governance level.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">You are proactive, not reactive.</span> Use the phrase "I anticipated..." or "I identified..." at least twice. This signals you are the kind of EA who adds value before being asked.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">You are tech-forward.</span> Mention your AI tool usage, Salesforce training, and project management tool proficiency. In 2026, this is a differentiator.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">You are adaptable across industries.</span> Three different industries. Three different executive styles. You can learn any business quickly.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">You are concise and executive-ready.</span> Demonstrate this through your answers. Short, structured, evidence-based. This is the most important message you can send, and you send it through your delivery, not your words.</li>
          </ol>
        </div>

        <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg mb-3">Salary Positioning</h3>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm mb-6">
          <div class="space-y-3">
            <div class="flex gap-3">
              <span class="text-secondary font-bold text-sm mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0">Anchor:</span>
              <p class="text-text-muted text-sm">"Based on my experience level and the NYC market, I am targeting a base salary in the $130,000 to $150,000 range, depending on the scope of the role and total compensation package."</p>
            </div>
            <div class="flex gap-3">
              <span class="text-secondary font-bold text-sm mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0">Target:</span>
              <p class="text-text-muted text-sm">$140,000 - $150,000 base (this positions you in the upper range for Senior EAs in NYC, which your experience justifies)</p>
            </div>
            <div class="flex gap-3">
              <span class="text-secondary font-bold text-sm mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0">Walk-away:</span>
              <p class="text-text-muted text-sm">$120,000 base (below this and you are undervaluing yourself given 10+ years of C-suite and IR experience)</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-4 p-4 bg-primary/[0.03] rounded-lg">
            <p class="text-sm text-primary font-semibold mb-2">Key Talking Points:</p>
            <ul class="space-y-1.5 text-sm text-text-muted">
              <li>"My last role was $125K base with a 25% bonus target and RSUs, for total compensation around $160K."</li>
              <li>"The NYC market for Senior EAs with investor relations experience is $120K-$165K base, and I believe my experience places me in the upper half of that range."</li>
              <li>"I am flexible on the exact number if the total compensation, including bonus and benefits, is competitive."</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-4 p-4 bg-secondary/5 rounded-lg">
            <p class="text-sm text-primary font-semibold mb-1">How to deflect early:</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm italic">"I would love to learn more about the scope of the role before we discuss numbers. Can you share what the budgeted range is for this position?"</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg mb-3">Must-Haves, Dealbreakers, and Nice-to-Haves</h3>
        <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-semibold text-green-700 text-sm mb-2">Must-Haves</p>
            <ul class="space-y-1.5 text-sm text-text-muted">
              <li>Direct support for a C-suite executive (CEO, CFO, COO) or equivalent</li>
              <li>Hybrid or in-office role in NYC</li>
              <li>Base salary at or above $120,000</li>
              <li>A culture that values EAs as strategic partners</li>
              <li>Room for scope expansion over time</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-semibold text-red-700 text-sm mb-2">Dealbreakers</p>
            <ul class="space-y-1.5 text-sm text-text-muted">
              <li>Micromanagement (executive approves every email)</li>
              <li>High EA turnover (3 EAs left within a year)</li>
              <li>No clarity on the role's value</li>
              <li>Salary below $110,000 base</li>
              <li>Fully remote with no in-person option</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-semibold text-secondary text-sm mb-2">Nice-to-Haves</p>
            <ul class="space-y-1.5 text-sm text-text-muted">
              <li>Investor relations or board-facing responsibilities</li>
              <li>Chief of Staff-adjacent scope</li>
              <li>Professional development budget</li>
              <li>Flexibility for culinary pursuits outside work</li>
              <li>Company in biotech, fintech, or finance</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 11. Career Landscape -->
    <section id="career-landscape" class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-warm">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Section 11</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-6">Career Landscape</h2>

        <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg mb-3">EA vs. Chief of Staff vs. Office Manager</h3>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
          <table class="w-full text-sm bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
            <thead>
              <tr class="bg-primary/5">
                <th class="text-left text-primary font-semibold p-3 text-xs uppercase tracking-wide">Dimension</th>
                <th class="text-left text-primary font-semibold p-3 text-xs uppercase tracking-wide">Executive Assistant</th>
                <th class="text-left text-primary font-semibold p-3 text-xs uppercase tracking-wide">Chief of Staff</th>
                <th class="text-left text-primary font-semibold p-3 text-xs uppercase tracking-wide">Office Manager</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="text-text-muted">
              <tr class="border-t border-primary/[0.06]"><td class="p-3 font-medium text-primary">Scope</td><td class="p-3">Supports 1-3 executives with calendar, communication, logistics, and project management</td><td class="p-3">Drives strategic initiatives, manages cross-functional projects, serves as executive proxy</td><td class="p-3">Manages office operations, facilities, vendors, and administrative team</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-t border-primary/[0.06]"><td class="p-3 font-medium text-primary">Reports to</td><td class="p-3">C-suite executive directly</td><td class="p-3">CEO or COO</td><td class="p-3">VP of Operations or COO</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-t border-primary/[0.06]"><td class="p-3 font-medium text-primary">Salary (NYC)</td><td class="p-3">$95,000 - $165,000</td><td class="p-3">$150,000 - $300,000</td><td class="p-3">$70,000 - $110,000</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-t border-primary/[0.06]"><td class="p-3 font-medium text-primary">Key differentiator</td><td class="p-3">Deep trust-based partnership with one executive</td><td class="p-3">Strategic project leadership across the organization</td><td class="p-3">Operational efficiency and team management</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-t border-primary/[0.06]"><td class="p-3 font-medium text-primary">Best for someone who</td><td class="p-3">Thrives on building a deep, strategic partnership and anticipating needs</td><td class="p-3">Wants to drive business outcomes and manage people/projects at scale</td><td class="p-3">Enjoys operational management and creating smooth-running environments</td></tr>
