        <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg mb-3">Career Progression from Senior EA</h3>
        <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-semibold text-primary text-sm mb-2">Path 1: EA to Chief of Staff <span class="font-normal text-text-muted">(Most common upward move)</span></p>
            <ul class="space-y-1 text-sm text-text-muted">
              <li>Build strategic project management experience alongside your EA duties</li>
              <li>Take on cross-functional initiatives that go beyond supporting one executive</li>
              <li>Develop financial literacy and business acumen</li>
              <li>Typical timeline: 2-4 years of Senior EA experience before transition</li>
              <li class="font-medium text-primary">Your investor relations and board-level experience already positions you closer to CoS than most EAs</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-semibold text-primary text-sm mb-2">Path 2: EA to Operations Leadership <span class="font-normal text-text-muted">(VP of Ops, Head of Admin)</span></p>
            <ul class="space-y-1 text-sm text-text-muted">
              <li>Focus on building systems, managing teams, and scaling processes</li>
              <li>Manage other EAs or administrative professionals</li>
              <li>Demonstrate ability to manage budgets and vendors at scale</li>
              <li>Typical timeline: 3-5 years, often through a "Head of Admin" intermediate role</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-semibold text-primary text-sm mb-2">Path 3: EA to Freelance/Consulting <span class="font-normal text-text-muted">(Fractional EA)</span></p>
            <ul class="space-y-1 text-sm text-text-muted">
              <li>Package your expertise as outcome-based consulting (not hourly)</li>
              <li>Target startups and scale-ups that cannot afford a full-time senior EA</li>
              <li>Build a personal brand and referral network</li>
              <li>Growing trend in 2026, especially among experienced EAs with niche industry expertise</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-semibold text-primary text-sm mb-2">Path 4: EA to Industry Specialist</p>
            <ul class="space-y-1 text-sm text-text-muted">
              <li>Your investor relations experience could lead to an IR Coordinator or IR Manager role</li>
              <li>Your biopharma experience could lead to clinical operations or regulatory affairs coordinator roles</li>
              <li>These paths use EA skills in more specialized, higher-paying functions</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg mb-3">Industry Trends for the EA Profession</h3>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
          <ul class="space-y-3 text-sm text-text-muted">
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">The strategic EA is here to stay.</span> Companies increasingly view senior EAs as force multipliers, not support staff. The title may not change, but the scope is expanding.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">AI is an accelerator, not a replacement.</span> AI tools handle drafting, summarization, and research faster, but the judgment, discretion, and relationship management that define great EAs cannot be automated. EAs who embrace AI tools become more valuable, not less.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">The talent gap is real.</span> According to Robert Half's 2026 report, the pool of qualified EA professionals is shrinking while demand grows. This is a seller's market for experienced EAs.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Professional certifications are becoming more common.</span> The CAP (Certified Administrative Professional) from IAAP and the PACE (Professional Administrative Certification of Excellence) are increasingly listed in job postings, though they are rarely required for senior roles.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">The fractional EA model is growing.</span> Platforms like Boldly, Belay, and Time Etc. are expanding the market for experienced EAs who want to work with multiple clients on their own terms. This trend supports your parallel freelance consultancy goal.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 12. Interview Tips -->
    <section id="interview-tips" class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-cream">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Section 12</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-6">Interview Tips</h2>

        <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg mb-3">Before the Interview</h3>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm mb-6">
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-text-muted">
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Research the format:</span> Ask the recruiter whether it is a panel, one-on-one, behavioral, or case-based interview. Knowing the format lets you prepare the right stories.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Confirm logistics:</span> Date, time (with timezone), platform (Zoom, Teams, Google Meet), and who you will be meeting with. Save the link somewhere you can find it fast.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Prepare your environment:</span> Choose a quiet, well-lit space. Test your camera, microphone, and internet connection the day before.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Dress one level up:</span> Match or slightly exceed the company's dress code. When in doubt, business casual is safe for most tech and startup interviews. Solid colors photograph better on camera than patterns.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Print or have the JD open:</span> Keep the job description visible during the interview so you can reference specific requirements.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg mb-3">During the Interview</h3>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm mb-6">
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-text-muted">
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Pause before answering:</span> Take 2-3 seconds to collect your thoughts before responding. This feels longer to you than it does to the interviewer. Silence is not awkward, it signals thoughtfulness.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Slow down:</span> Most people speak 20-30% faster when nervous. Consciously slow your pace. If you catch yourself speeding up, take a breath.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Use the STAR method:</span> For behavioral questions ("Tell me about a time when..."), structure your answer: Situation, Task, Action, Result. This keeps you focused and prevents rambling.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Keep answers to 60-90 seconds:</span> For most questions, 1-2 minutes is the sweet spot. If your answer is running past 2 minutes, wrap it up. You can always ask "Would you like me to go deeper on any part of that?"</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Mirror their energy:</span> Match the interviewer's pace and tone. If they are casual and relaxed, you can be too. If they are formal, stay professional.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Show, don't tell:</span> Instead of saying "I'm a great communicator," tell a story that demonstrates it. Evidence is always more convincing than claims.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">It's okay to not know:</span> If you do not know the answer, say so honestly. "I have not worked with that specific tool, but here is how I would approach learning it" is a strong answer.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg mb-3">Zoom / Video Interview Tips</h3>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm mb-6">
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-text-muted">
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Camera at eye level:</span> Stack your laptop on books if needed. Looking down at the camera makes you appear disengaged.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Look at the camera, not the screen:</span> When speaking, look directly at the camera lens. This creates the impression of eye contact. When listening, you can look at their face on screen.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Close unnecessary tabs and apps:</span> Notifications popping up are distracting. Put your phone on silent and face-down.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Use a neutral background:</span> A clean wall, bookshelf, or a tasteful virtual background. Avoid busy or distracting backgrounds.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Have water nearby:</span> A dry throat mid-answer is uncomfortable. Keep a glass of water within reach.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Use headphones:</span> They improve audio quality and reduce echo. Wired earbuds work well and are less distracting than large headphones.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg mb-3">Body Language</h3>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm mb-6">
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-text-muted">
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Sit up straight but relaxed:</span> Lean slightly forward to show engagement. Avoid slouching or leaning back too far.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Use natural hand gestures:</span> Talking with your hands (visible on camera) makes you appear more dynamic and authentic.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Smile naturally:</span> Especially when greeting and when the conversation is light. A genuine smile builds rapport faster than any talking point.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Nod while listening:</span> Small nods show you are engaged and processing what they are saying.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg mb-3">After the Interview</h3>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-text-muted">
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Send a thank-you email within 24 hours:</span> Reference something specific from the conversation. Keep it brief (3-5 sentences). This is not optional.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Debrief while it is fresh:</span> Write down the questions you were asked, how you answered, and what you wish you had said differently. This is valuable for future interviews.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Follow up if you have not heard back:</span> After the timeline they gave you, a polite check-in email is appropriate. One follow-up, not multiple.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

  </main>
